<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6952&amp;p=67547#p67547</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6952&amp;p=67547#p67547"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[4 power pads with NES satellite or 4-Score]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6952&amp;p=67547#p67547"><![CDATA[
Hacking a game looks easier at first, and I guess it is if the changes are simple enough.  In the long run it could be a major up-hill battle to add/remove even the most basic features, first issue being working within whatever data compression it may use, for the background tilemaps (nametables), if nothing else.  It going to be much easier to write something from scratch.<br /><br />I have a Satellite somewhere (I don't have any C-cell batteries though, it takes 6 of them).  Maybe I could take it apart, but the outlook is extremely grim, it would almost surely require extra hardware which would have never been used.  Then since it's transmitted as infra-red, it would have been an outright waste of electricity to transmit unused bits.  I remember the zapper/controller switch was right by the 2nd port, I'm guessing it just hooks it up for the 2nd port.  I don't know if anything ever used the zapper on any other port (other than the unlicensed game Chiller, which could use 2 of them).<br /><br />I've been curious about testing the powerpad to see if it responds to hits from drum sticks or mallets, but I haven't tried that out.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Wed Sep 15, 2010 6:04 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
